  "topic_name": "Sound",
  "canonical_explanation": {
    "text": "Sound is produced by vibrating objects. It requires a medium (solid, liquid, or gas) to travel and cannot travel through vacuum. Sound travels fastest in solids and slowest in gases. The characteristics of sound include loudness (depends on amplitude), pitch (depends on frequency), and quality or timbre (distinguishes different sources). An echo is the reflection of sound from a hard surface. For an echo to be heard distinctly, the reflecting surface must be at least 17 metres away. Noise pollution is unwanted sound that can be harmful to health.",
    "rules": [
      "Sound is produced by vibration of objects.",
      "Sound requires a medium to travel.",
      "Sound cannot travel through vacuum.",
      "Speed of sound: solids > liquids > gases.",
      "Loudness depends on amplitude of vibration.",
      "Pitch depends on frequency of vibration.",
      "Quality (timbre) distinguishes sounds of same pitch.",
      "Echo: reflection of sound (minimum distance ~17 m)."
    ]
  },
